  "prompt": "What is the coefficient of x^9 in (1+x) (1+x^2) \u2026 (1+x^100)?",
  "response": "To find the coefficient of \\(x^9\\) in the expansion of \\( P(x) = (1 + x)(1 + x^2)(1 + x^3) \\cdots (1 + x^{100}) \\), we need to look at all possible ways to form \\(x^9\\) by choosing \\(x^k\\) from different factors of the product. \n\nEach term in the expansion is formed by choosing either 1 or \\(x^m\\) (where \\(m\\) is an integer from 1 to 100) from each factor. Therefore, to form \\(x^9\\), we need to find a set of exponents whose sum is 9. \n\nLet's identify all the potential combinations of these exponents:\n\n- Choosing \\(x^9\\) directly from \\( (1 + x^9) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^8\\) from \\( (1 + x^8) \\) and \\(x^1\\) from \\( (1 + x) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^7\\) from \\( (1 + x^7) \\) and \\(x^2\\) from \\( (1 + x^2) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^6\\) from \\( (1 + x^6) \\) and \\(x^3\\) from \\( (1 + x^3) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^5\\) from \\( (1 + x^5) \\) and \\(x^4\\) from \\( (1 + x^4) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^5\\) from \\( (1 + x^5) \\), \\(x^3\\) from \\( (1 + x^3) \\), and \\(x^1\\) from \\( (1 + x) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^4\\) from \\( (1 + x^4) \\), \\(x^3\\) from \\( (1 + x^3) \\), and \\(x^2\\) from \\( (1 + x^2) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^4\\) from \\( (1 + x^4) \\), \\(x^2\\) twice from \\( (1 + x^2) \\), and \\(x^1\\) from \\( (1 + x) \\).\n\n- Choosing \\(x^3\\) thrice from \\( (1 + x^3) \\).\n\nFrom these combinations, we expect the number of ways to form \\(x^9\\). To count this:\n\n1. The term \\(x^9\\) directly provides 1 way.\n2. Choosing \\(x^8\\) and \\(x^1\\) provides 1 way.\n3. Choosing \\(x^7\\) and \\(x^2\\) provides 1 way.\n4. Choosing \\(x^6\\) and \\(x^3\\) provides 1 way.\n5. Choosing \\(x^5\\) and \\(x^4\\) provides 1 way.\n6. Choosing \\(x^5\\), \\(x^3\\), and \\(x^1\\) provides 1 way.\n7. Choosing \\(x^4\\), \\(x^3\\), and \\(x^2\\) provides 1 way.\n8. Choosing \\(x^4\\), \\(x^2\\), \\(x^2\\), and \\(x^1\\) provides 1 way.\n9. Choosing \\(x^3\\), \\(x^3\\), and \\(x^3\\) provides 1 way.\n\nSumming these, the number of ways to form the coefficient of \\(x^9\\) is \\(1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 9\\).\n\nTherefore, the coefficient of \\(x^9\\) in \\( (1 + x)(1 + x^2)(1 + x^3) \\cdots (1 + x^{100}) \\) is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{9}\n\\]",
